{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522214"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13812"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13812"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.08,0.57,0.33,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49111"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6429"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34146"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"2383"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31745"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49111"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-week history of eye dryness and photophobia in the right eye. He reports accidentally splashing a household cleaning product in his eye about a month ago, which caused significant pain at the time. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His right eye is visualised (Image). Examination of the left eye is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conjunctivitis","Corneal abrasion","Pterygium","Symblepharon","Trichiasis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Esymblepharon\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterized by adhesion between the conjunctiva of the eyelid and the eyeball. The history of chemical exposure from a household cleaning product, followed by the symptoms of dryness and photophobia, and the visible band of tissue are all consistent with this diagnosis. Symblepharon often results from chemical burns or severe inflammatory conditions (Steven-Johnson Syndrome, lichen planus, sarcoid, granulomatosis, chronic chlamydia infections or epidemic keratoconjunctivitis).   It is rarely congenital. It may also present with burning sensation, decreased vision, diplopia, entropion or lagophthalmos, depending on the severity of injury.  It is a clinical diagnosis with fluorescein staining and careful eyelid eversion, and treatment is with surgical repair and treating the associated disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPterygium\u003C/strong\u003E is a wedge-shaped fibrovascular growth that extends from the conjunctiva onto the cornea. While it can cause similar symptoms of eye irritation and redness, it typically has a more characteristic triangular appearance and is not associated with a history of chemical injury and would not cause photophobia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation of the conjunctiva that can cause redness, discharge, and eye discomfort. However, it does not typically result in adhesions between the eyelid and eyeball as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorneal abrasion\u003C/strong\u003E is a scratch or scrape on the surface of the cornea. While it can be caused by chemical exposure and lead to significant pain and photophobia, it would not cause the visible adhesion seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrichiasis\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where the eyelashes grow inward and rub against the eye, causing irritation which may cause erythema. It is not associated with the trauma, photophobia or dryness as is in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Symblepharon is characterized by abnormal adhesion between the conjunctiva of the eyelid and the eyeball, often resulting from chemical burns or severe inflammatory conditions.","Fluorescein staining and careful eyelid eversion are important diagnostic steps in identifying symblepharon in a primary care setting."],"references":["Chong K, Fowler B, Bunya V, Dryden S et al. Symblepharon. In: EyeWiki American Academy of Opthalmology [online]. 2024. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Symblepharon","Jeffrey R, Dobes J, Chen F. Eye Injuries: Understanding ocular trauma. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2022:51(7). Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/july/eye-injuries"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34146"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13812"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20755"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20755"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/BeGQ5s6FsffifODQwNIWkKWCL0TXKk.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/BeGQ5s6FsffifODQwNIWkKWCL0TXKk.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}